<br>
<h4 style="text-align:center;">Project Day 4: Govinda Halli and Jangala Colony</h4>
<p>On the fourth day of the project, we had only planned to go to Govinda Halli, but the head of the Jangala Colony of Kothakota became interested in our project and asked us if we could visit there as well. We were able to get 200 vaccines for this day from the Kothakota PHC. We visited Govinda Halli, which has a population of 700 people, in the morning. We followed the same structure as previously, starting with some words from myself and my mom as well as the leaders of the village and health specialists from the PHC, after which everyone who wished could get their vaccine. Additionally, MLA Reddy came to see this morning program and spoke to the people of Govinda Halli about the importance of the vaccination. Because of his visit, local journalists and newspapers came to report on our project and take pictures of the program. At Govinda Halli we vaccinated 100 people who all received incentive bags after their vaccination. After Govinda Halli, we went to the Jangala colony for afternoon programming. All of the locations we had visited previously were villages, and although the people who lived there were isolated and did not have much technology or media access, they were still towns with individual houses and public buildings such as schoolhouses, small medical shops, and small food carts. Jangala Colony was a slum behind an oil extraction plant and gas station, and the people there lived in immense poverty with almost no resources closeby. Because of this, their fear of the vaccine was much more heightened and many left the colony or hid in their rooms when we came, thinking that they would be forced to take the vaccine. Once our programming started, more people began to show up from the colony after hearing what I and the other speakers said about the importance and safety of the vaccine. One of the most meaningful moments of my project took place at Jangala colony: I met a young girl, around 20 years old, who had been stricken with polio when she was young because she couldn’t get vaccinated against it. when I was able to help her receive her COVID vaccine, it truly was so special and hugely impacted my outlook on what exactly I was doing. At Jangala colony we were able to vaccinate another 100 people.<p><br>

